The RESNA Student Design Competition (SDC) is designed to promote and foster innovative and creative design of assistive technology hardware and software to be used by or in support of individuals with disabilities. SDC is also designed to encourage, support, and mentor students in various disciplines to become aware of and involved in the assistive technology (AT) and rehabilitation engineering fields.

In collaboration with the Alternative &amp; Augmentative Communication &ndash; Rehabilitation Engineering Research Center (AAC-RERC) and Pennsylvania State University, students were required to design rich-media web pages into a blog site for submission of their design to the judging panel.  Through the use of blogging tools, submissions were cataloged and permanently available to advancing students, as well as professionals in the AT and rehabilitation industry. To view all the SDC web submissions, please visit: http://aac-rerc.psu.edu/wordpressmu/RESNA-SDC/resna/

A team of scholars and assistive technology practitioners reviewed each submission to ensure adherence to the structured outline of the submission requirements.  Evaluation criteria included:

Design adequately addresses problem posed by the student/client team;
Prototype uses sound engineering or design approaches, which promote safety and use by targeted client/population;
Creativity is evident in the proposed solution, and it represents a new addition to the field of assistive technology;
Students have evaluated and/or validated the prototype in an iterative way with their targeted client/population;
Students are capable of communicating their ideas well, within structured guidelines, without errors or omissions; and
Prototype is functional, as viewed in the product video.


Of the papers submitted to RESNA, six papers and their authors were selected as finalists.  These teams attended the RESNA/NCART 2016 conference in Arlington, Virginia to present their designs to approximately 600 individuals, including technologists, health and social service practitioners, academics, government representatives, seniors, people with disabilities, caregivers and businesses which serve these constituents. A one year full RESNA membership was provided by RESNA to all finalists.  Teams competed in an onsite competition where First Place, Second Place, and Third Place winners  were named.  The finalists presented their designs during the general conference as one of the 75-minute Platform sessions.  All teams were recognized during the RESNA Awards Ceremony and presented with Certificates for their SDC participation. The student papers were included in the 2016 Conference Proceedings which may be found on the RESNA website http://www.resna.org/sites/default/files/conference/2016/sdc2016/index.html. 

